Here's the complete migration from ASP.NET WebForms to ASP.NET Core 8, addressing all `Thread.Abort` patterns.

## Pattern Inventory

Your code has **3 Thread.Abort patterns**:

| Location | Pattern | API |
|---|---|---|
| `btnExport_Click` | Request termination | `Response.End()` |
| `btnRedirect_Click` | Request termination | `Response.Redirect(url, true)` Ă— 3 |
| `btnRedirect_Click` | Control flow | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` |

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`). All three patterns must be replaced with cooperative alternatives.

---

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // POST /report/export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Return a FileResult â€” the framework handles headers and response lifecycle.
        // No Response.Clear/Write/End needed; MVC result objects replace all of that.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    // POST /report/redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAction()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Redirect() returns a 302 result â€” no thread abort, no endResponse.
            // Execution continues normally after return.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) â€” it doesn't exist in modern .NET.
        // OperationCanceledException is the cooperative equivalent if needed.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ return ""; }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

## What Changed and Why

### 1. `Response.End()` â†’ return a result object
**Old:** `Response.End()` called `Thread.Abort` internally to halt execution.
**New:** Just `return` an `IActionResult`. MVC handles the response lifecycle. The `File()` helper sets Content-Type, Content-Disposition, and writes the body â€” no manual header manipulation needed.

### 2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` â†’ `return Redirect(url)`
**Old:** The `true` parameter called `Thread.Abort` to prevent code after the redirect from executing.
**New:** `return Redirect(url)` exits the action method normally. Because you `return`, no code runs after it â€” no abort needed.

### 3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` â†’ removed entirely
**Old:** WebForms required swallowing `ThreadAbortException` because `Response.Redirect` threw it as a side effect.
**New:** No exception is thrown. The catch block is dead code â€” remove it. If you need to handle client disconnects, use `HttpContext.RequestAborted`:

```csharp
try
{
    await LongRunningWork(HttpContext.RequestAborted);
}
catch (OperationCanceledException)
{
    // Client disconnected â€” clean up if needed
}
```

---

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---|---|
| **Code after redirect still runs** | In WebForms, `endResponse: true` prevented this via abort. In MVC, forgetting `return` before `Redirect()` means subsequent code executes. Always `return Redirect(...)`. |
| **Manual Response writes in MVC** | Don't use `Response.Body.WriteAsync()` then return a result â€” you'll get "response already started" errors. Use result objects exclusively. |
| **Null reference on `User.Identity`** | In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be null if no auth middleware is configured. Use `?.` (shown above). |
| **`ThreadAbortException` in libraries** | If shared libraries catch `ThreadAbortException`, replace with `OperationCanceledException` and pass `CancellationToken` through the call chain. |
| **WebForms event model is gone** | `btnExport_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)` doesn't exist in MVC. Map to controller actions with `[HttpPost]` and route to them via forms or AJAX. |

---

## Routing Setup

Replace WebForms button postbacks with standard form submissions:

```html
<!-- Old WebForms -->
<asp:Button ID="btnExport" runat="server" OnClick="btnExport_Click" />

<!-- New Razor/HTML -->
<form method="post" asp-controller="Report" asp-action="Export">
    <button type="submit">Export</button>
</form>
```

This covers the full migration. The core principle: **ASP.NET Core uses return values for flow control, not thread aborts.** Every `Response.End/Redirect(url, true)` becomes a `return SomeActionResult()`.
